Okay, so here's an overview of what I'm going to talk about today. So first I'm going to talk about

00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:31.120
different kinds of graphics and what we'd use them for.

00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:38.080
So there are static versus interactive graphics. Static graphics are, you know, the traditional

00:00:39.680 --> 00:00:43.279
plots that you would see. You might print them out, you can't interact with them. And

00:00:43.279 --> 00:00:47.599
interactive ones obviously are things that you can interact with by, say, using your mouse.

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:56.080
There are graphics for different purposes. So for example, you might have a graphic for

00:00:56.160 --> 00:00:59.919
presentation, like if you're creating a report that you want to display to somebody, or for

00:00:59.919 --> 00:01:07.040
publication. And there's data graphics for exploring your data. So if you're still in the

00:01:08.080 --> 00:01:14.080
data analysis process or, you know, in the exploratory data analysis phase, and you're

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:20.239
trying to learn something about your data, that's another purpose for using a data graphic,

00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:23.199
as opposed to for presentations.

00:01:23.519 --> 00:01:26.959
So after that, I'm going to talk about the nuts and bolts of actually creating

00:01:26.959 --> 00:01:32.320
interactive graphics with Shiny. And so we'll get into some code. And after that,

00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:38.559
I'm going to talk about using, creating Shiny gadgets, which are, those are, it's using Shiny

00:01:38.559 --> 00:01:44.959
for the data exploration phase. And this is a new feature that we've added in Shiny 0.13,

00:01:44.959 --> 00:01:49.279
which was released a month ago. Oh, and I should also mention that the interactive

00:01:49.760 --> 00:01:54.000
